1. The Two-Step Animation Architecture
Creating an animation in CSS requires a two-step workflow:

Define the Timeline (@keyframes): Outline the visual stages and structural benchmarks of the animation.

Apply to the Element (animation-* properties): Attach that timeline to a specific class or tag and configure its speed, behavior, and iteration limits.

2. Step 1: Defining Timelines with @keyframes
The @keyframes rule acts as the timeline map. You can define state transitions using simple keywords (from and to) or detailed percentage stages (0% through 100%) for complex movements.

CSS
/* Simple Two-State Keyframe */
@keyframes fadeIn {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to   { opacity: 1; }
}

/* Multi-Stage Complex Keyframe (e.g., a bouncing ball) */
@keyframes bounceAndMove {
  0%   { transform: translateY(0);   background-color: red; }
  50%  { transform: translateY(-50px); background-color: orange; }
  100% { transform: translateY(0) translateX(100px); background-color: green; }
}
3. Step 2: Attaching Animation Sub-Properties
Once a keyframe timeline is declared, you attach it to an element using individual sub-properties:

animation-name: Matches the exact custom string name defined in your @keyframes rule.

animation-duration: Controls how long the timeline takes to complete a single cycle (e.g., 2s or 500ms).

animation-timing-function: Manages acceleration curves. Options include linear (constant speed), ease-in (starts slow), ease-out (ends slow), or custom cubic-bezier() curves.

animation-delay: Sets a pause threshold before the element fires its initial execution sequence.

animation-iteration-count: Dictates how many times the sequence replays. Accepts a specific integer (e.g., 3) or infinite to loop forever.

animation-direction: Controls playback paths. Options include normal, reverse, alternate (plays forward, then walks backward repeatedly), and alternate-reverse.

animation-fill-mode: Determines what styles stick to the element when the timeline finishes. forwards forces the element to stay locked at its final 100% keyframe style rather than snapping instantly back to its original raw style.

4. The Clean Industry Shorthand (animation)
To save time and keep your code clean, you can combine all sub-properties into a single shortcut declaration:

CSS
/* Shorthand Order: name | duration | timing-function | delay | iteration-count | direction | fill-mode */
.loader-ball {
  animation: bounceAndMove 2s ease-in-out 500ms infinite alternate forwards;
}
Comprehensive Student Code Lab: The Loading Spinner
Copy this complete standalone script into VS Code to practice stacking keyframe rotation loops:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSS Animation Lab</title>
    <style>
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }

        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            min-height: 100vh;
            background-color: #111; /* Dark theme */
        }

        /* 1. Define the rotation timeline */
        @keyframes spin {
            0% { 
                transform: rotate(0deg); 
                border-top-color: #007bff; /* Blue */
            }
            50% {
                border-top-color: #e83e8c; /* Pink midpoint shift */
            }
            100% { 
                transform: rotate(360deg); 
                border-top-color: #007bff; 
            }
        }

        /* 2. Style the element and apply the animation timeline */
        .spinner {
            width: 80px;
            height: 80px;
            border: 8px solid #333; /* Dark background ring track */
            border-radius: 50%;     /* Crisp circle box */
            
            /* Apply shorthand animation */
            animation: spin 1.2s linear infinite;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="spinner"></div>
</body>
</html>